    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 14, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🇨🇳 Stanford's AI Report: China Just Showed Up to the Benchmark War\n\nStanford's 2026 AI Index dropped this week, and the headline is that the US lead in AI model performance shrank from 9.26% to 1.70% — while American labs have been outspending China 23 to 1.\n\n- **The performance gap:** US and Chinese models have traded places at the top of rankings multiple times since early 2025. SWE-bench coding scores went from 60% to near 100% in a single year.\n- **The transparency catch:** The Foundation Model Transparency Index fell from 58 to 40 — major AI labs are now less open about training data, compute, and risk disclosures than they were last year.\n\n*The US is outspending China 23-to-1 and the gap is 1.7 percentage points. Extremely efficient.*\n\n**Sources:** [Stanford HAI](https://hai.stanford.edu/ai-index/2026-ai-index-report) | [SiliconAngle](https://siliconangle.com/2026/04/13/stanford-hais-2026-ai-index-reveals-china-u-s-now-neck-neck-race-global-dominance/) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/13/stanford-report-highlights-growing-disconnect-between-ai-insiders-and-everyone-else/)\n\n---\n\n## 💸 PwC Found That AI Is Printing Money — For 20% of Companies\n\nPwC surveyed 1,217 senior executives and discovered that 74% of AI's economic gains are going to 20% of companies, which is either a business strategy insight or a description of a pyramid scheme.\n\n- **What the winners do:** They use AI to reinvent their business model and chase \"industry convergence\" — not just cut costs. They generate 7.2x more value with 4 percentage points higher profit margins.\n- **What everyone else is doing:** Pilot mode. Producing presentations about AI potential. Stuck.\n\n*Three-quarters of the gains. One-fifth of the companies. Someone is going to write a very optimistic LinkedIn post about this.*\n\n**Sources:** [PwC](https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/news-room/press-releases/2026/pwc-2026-ai-performance-study.html)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 NVIDIA Spent National Robotics Week Announcing Its Entire Physical AI Stack\n\nNVIDIA used National Robotics Week to unveil Isaac GR00T open models (robots understand natural language and perform multistep tasks), Newton 1.0 physics engine (generally available), Cosmos world models for training at scale, and RoboLab — a high-fidelity simulation benchmark.\n\n- **The strategy:** Full-stack cloud-to-robot workflow: simulation → robot learning → edge computing. NVIDIA wants to be the infrastructure layer for physical AI the way it became the infrastructure layer for generative AI.\n- **The business logic:** Not subtle. At all.\n\n**Sources:** [NVIDIA Blog](https://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/national-robotics-week-2026/) | [Design News](https://www.designnews.com/automation/national-robotics-week-2026-highlights-ai-driven-automation-physical-ai-s-manufacturing-impact)\n\n---\n\n## 🏠 Robots Succeed at 12% of Household Tasks. The Hype Is Doing Fine.\n\nBuried in Stanford's AI Index: despite all the physical AI investment, autonomous robots succeed at roughly 12% of everyday household tasks.\n\n- **For context:** The humanoid robotics sector is projected to draw $20 billion+ in investment in 2026 alone. The robots can manage about one in eight things you'd ask them to do at home.\n- **The remaining 88%:** Fold laundry without destroying it. Pick a specific object from a cluttered table. Survive a kitchen.\n\n*$20 billion for a 12% success rate. Series A investors have funded stranger things.*\n\n**Sources:** [Stanford HAI](https://hai.stanford.edu/ai-index/2026-ai-index-report) | [IEEE Spectrum](https://spectrum.ieee.org/state-of-ai-index-2026)"
  }
